\begin_layout Subsection
Membrane Potential and Action Potential
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Membrane Potential
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Neurons usually maintain a difference in electric potential across its cell
 membrane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Unequal distribution of charged ions(Na+,K+,Ca2+, cl- etc) accounts for
 this membrane potential difference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cell membrane has selectively permeable ion channels which facilitates the
 movement of corrensponding ions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{m}=V_{in}-V_{out}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Action Potential
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
signals are processed across an excitable neuron in the form of propogating
 spikes or action potential.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A slight decrease in membrane potential makes membrane more permeable to
 Na+ than K+, and a positive feedback loop facilitates further depolarization
 to form a sharp peak in the voltage across the membrane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Action potential is an all or nothing event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename requirements/action_potential.jpg
	scale 30
	rotateOrigin rightBottom

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hodgkin Huxley Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
About the model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
H & H model 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The Hodgkin-Huxley Model is a mathematical model for the initiation and
 propogation of action potential across a neurons based on the dynamic behaviour
 of the conductance of different ions across the membrane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It is a set of differential equations which is mostly derived from emperical
 data from different set of Voltage clamp experiments conducted on squid
 giant axon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Alan Lloyd Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley received the Nobel Prize in phhysiology
 or Medicine for the same
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Differential Equations 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
